### 5.5 compareDocuments

**Purpose**: Compare two document versions with semantic analysis, change classification, and negotiation recommendations.

**Input Parameters**:
```json
{
  "doc_id_a": "doc-123",
  "doc_id_b": "doc-456",
  "comparison_depth": "semantic",
  "our_party": "Acme Corp",
  "include_recommendations": true
}
```

| Parameter | Type | Required | Description |
|-----------|------|----------|-------------|
| doc_id_a | string | Yes | First document (typically older) |
| doc_id_b | string | Yes | Second document (typically newer) |
| comparison_depth | string | No | "text_diff", "clause_level", or "semantic" |
| our_party | string | No | Which party we represent |
| include_recommendations | boolean | No | Include negotiation recommendations |

**Output**:
```json
{
  "success": true,
  "changes": [
    {
      "type": "substantive",
      "clause": "Limitation of Liability",
      "description": "Liability cap changed from 12 months to 24 months",
      "risk_level": "medium"
    }
  ],
  "summary": "15 substantive changes, 8 cosmetic changes",
  "recommendations": [...]
}
```

**When to Use**:
- Reviewing contract versions
- Negotiation preparation
- Tracking changes over time
- Due diligence reviews

**When NOT to Use**:
- Reading a single document (use readDocument)
- Making edits (use editDocument)

**Failure Modes**:
- Either document not found
- Documents too different for meaningful comparison
- Comparison timeout for large documents

